Having united the Čech cochain complex with the de Rham cochain complex in a single commutative diagram, all that's left is
using this diagram to prove the existence of the actual isomorphism. As with the Mayer-Vietoris sequence, this
is best done purely algebraicly and requires a bit of a detour into homological algebra.
\section{Double Complexes}
The diagram we constructed in the last paragraph is an instance of a more abstract phenomenon:
\begin{definition}[Double Complex]
	A \underline{double complex} is a $\ZZ \times \ZZ$-graded vector space
	$C^{*, *} := \{C^{p,q}\}_{p,q \in \ZZ}$ together with linear
	maps
	\[
		\rmd^{p,q}_h: C^{p, q} \to C^{p + 1, q}
		\quad
		\text{ and }
		\quad
		\rmd^{p,q}_v: C^{p,q} \to C^{p, q + 1}
	\]
	for every $p,q \in \ZZ$ (with $\rmd^{*, *}_h$ as usual referring
	to the unique linear map that restricts to $\rmd^{p,q}_h$ on $C^{p,q}$ and
	similar for $\rmd^{*, *}_v$),  with $\dvb, \dhb$ each being
	nilpotent i.e:
	\[
		\dvb \circ \dvb = \dhb \circ \dhb = 0
	\]
	and with the following diagram commuting:
	% https://q.uiver.app/#q=WzAsNCxbMCwwLCJDXntwLCBxKzF9Il0sWzAsMSwiQ157cCxxfSJdLFsxLDEsIkNee3AgKyAxLCBxfSJdLFsxLDAsIkNee3ArMSxxKzF9Il0sWzEsMCwiXFxybWRfdl57cCxxfSJdLFsxLDIsIlxccm1kXntwLHF9X2giLDJdLFswLDMsIlxccm1kXntwLHErMX1faCJdLFsyLDMsIlxccm1kXntwKzEscX1fdiIsMl1d
	\[\begin{tikzcd}
		{C^{p, q+1}} & {C^{p+1,q+1}} \\
		{C^{p,q}} & {C^{p + 1, q}}
		\arrow["{\rmd^{p,q+1}_h}", from=1-1, to=1-2]
		\arrow["{\rmd_v^{p,q}}", from=2-1, to=1-1]
		\arrow["{\rmd^{p,q}_h}"', from=2-1, to=2-2]
		\arrow["{\rmd^{p+1,q}_v}"', from=2-2, to=1-2]
	\end{tikzcd}\]
\end{definition}
\begin{remark}
	Some authors (e.g. \cite{weibel_introduction_1994}) prefer to define these maps as  being
	anti-commutative instead of commutative. While this saves some signs in some places (e.g. in
	the definition of homology of a chain complex), it also adds them in other places and since
	the later dominates in this thesis, we are going to follow \cite{bott_differential_1982} and
	assume commutativity.
\end{remark}

Double complexes are a powerful tool and not only can they be seen as a generalization of
cochain complexes\footnote{
	The high-brow approach to this would be to define chain complexes over general abelian categories,
	then a double complex is "just" a chain complex of chain complexes, but let's not do that.
}, they also can be reduced back to a cochain complex by summing up their diagonals:
\begin{definition}[Associated Cochain complex]
	Given a double complex $C^{*, *}$ with maps $\dvb, \dhb$ the
	\textbf{associated cochain complex of $C^{*, *}$}, denoted as
	$C^*(C^{*, *})$ is the cochain complex defined as:
	\[
		C^n(C^{*, *}) \coloneqq \bigoplus_{n = p + q} C^{p,q}
	\]
	with the differential $\rmd^n: C^n \to C^{n + 1}$ being defined as:
	\[
		\rmd^n \coloneqq \bigoplus_{p + q = n} (-1)^p \rmd^{p,q}_v + \rmd^{p,q}_h
	\]
\end{definition}
This actually being a cochain complex remains to be proven:
\begin{lemma}
	For a given double complex $C^{*, *}$ with maps $\dvb$ and $\dhb$
	the associated cochain complex is a cochain complex.
\end{lemma}
\begin{proof}
	We have to proof that $\rmd^*$ is nilpotent. Let $c \in C^{p,q}$ for some $p,q \in \ZZ$.
	Then:
	\begin{align*}
		(\rmd^{p + q + 1} \circ \rmd^{p + q})(c)
		&=
		\rmd^{p + q + 1}((-1)^p \rmd^{p,q}_v(c) + \rmd^{p,q}_h(c)) \\
		&=
(-1)^p (\overbrace{
				(\rmd^{p, q + 1}_h \circ \rmd^{p,q}_v)(c)
				- (\rmd^{p + 1, q}_v \circ \rmd^{p,q}_h)(c)
			)
		}^{\text{commutative}}) \\
		&\quad+ \underbrace{
			(\rmd^{p + 1, q}_h \circ \rmd^{p,q}_h)(c)
		}_{\text{nilpotent}}
		+
		\underbrace{
			(\rmd^{p, q + 1}_v \circ \rmd^{p,q}_v)(c)
		}_{\text{nilpotent}} \\
		&= 0 \qedhere
	\end{align*}
\end{proof}
But the name of the game is homological algebra, not cochain complex algebra, so the logical
next step is taking the cohomology of this:
\begin{definition}[Cohomology of a Double Complex]
	For a given double complex $C^{*,*}$ we define its
	\underline{cohomology} as the cohomology of the
	associated cochain complex, in notation:
	\[
		H^*(C^{*,*}) := H^*(C^*(C^{*,*}))
	\]
\end{definition}

Double complexes form a fascinating part of commutative algebra, being used to define such
marvelous (and mysterious) tools like spectral sequences and one could study them on their own,
but we are only interested in using them to proof our statement and are therefore going to add
some additional assumptions about them. Particularly we are going to assume that all future
double complexes are non-trivial only in the upper-right quadrant i.e. $C^{p,k} = 0$ for $p <
0$ or $k < 0$.

The Čech-de Rham double complex does not really fit this assumption, having an additional
row and column. We are going to treat these not as part of the double complex, but as an
augmentation of it and then prove de Rhams theorem by proving that the cohomology of the double
complex is isomorphic to the cohomologies of these augmentations. This is not true for all
double complexes and augmentations, but with some convenient assumptions it is true:
\begin{theorem}
\label{theorem:augmentation_iso_homology}
Let $C^{*,*}$ be a double complex, $(A^*, \delta)$ a cochain
complex. If for every $n \geq 0$ there is a map
\[
	\alpha^n: A^n \to C^{n,0}
\]
such that the following diagram commutes:
