\section{Explicit Isomorphism}
So far we only know that an isomorphism between de Rham and Čech cohomology exists, but not
how it acts concretely. But by looking closely at the proof above we can find an quite explicit
description of this isomorphism, using the map $r$ that we constructed to prove exactness of
the infinite Mayer-Vietoris sequence.

The isomorphism maps a cochain $[c] \in \hat{H}^k(X, \mathfrak{U})$ to an element $[j(c)] \in
H^k(\Omega^{*, *}(\mathfrak{U}))$ with $j(c) \in \Omega^{k, 0}(\mathfrak{U})$. Then, after $k$
iterations of $\rmd \circ r$ and some sign changes\footnote{the first iteration contains a $(-1)^{k - 1}$,
the next a $(-1)^{k - 2}$ etc.}, this gets mapped to a homologous element
$(-1)^{(k(k + 1)/2) - k}(\rmd \circ r)^k(j(c)) \in \Omega^{0, k}(\mathfrak{U})$, whose components can
be glued together to a closed $k$-form on $M$. Locally this can be made even more explicit:
\begin{lemma}
	Let $\cdual{\alpha_0 \dots \alpha_k} \in \hat{H}^k(M, \mathfrak{U})$. Define $\Alpha_{i_1 \dots i_\ell}$
	as the $k - \ell$ multi-index $\alpha_0, \dots, \alpha_k$ without $\alpha_{i_1}, \dots, \alpha_{i_\ell}$.
	Then for any $0 \leq \ell \leq k$ and $i_1 < \dots < i_\ell$:
	\[
		(\rmd \circ r)^\ell(j(c))_{\Alpha_{i_1 \dots i_\ell}}
			= \ell! (-1)^{i_1 + \dots + i_\ell} (\rmd \rho_{i_1} \wedge \dots \wedge \rmd \rho_{i_\ell})
	\]
	with all other components (that aren't permutations of this) being zero.
\end{lemma}
\begin{proof}
We proof this by induction, for $\ell = 0$ (i.e. for the complete multiindex $\Alpha$) we have
\[
	j(\cdual{\alpha_0, \dots, \alpha_k})_{\alpha_0,\dots,\alpha_k}
		= 1
		= 0! (-1)^0
\]
This fits the lemma (since the empty wedge product is defined as 1).

As the inductive step, assume it is true for $\ell - 1$, then for $\ell$ we have:
\begin{align*}
	(\rmd &\circ r)^\ell(j(\cdual{\alpha_0, \dots, \alpha_k}))_{A_{i_1 \dots i_\ell}}
		= ((\rmd \circ r) \circ (\rmd \circ r)^{\ell - 1} \circ i)(\cdual{\alpha_0, \dots, \alpha_k})))_{A_{i_1 \dots i_\ell}}\\
		&= \rmd \left((r \circ (\rmd \circ r)^{\ell - 1} \circ i)(\cdual{\alpha_0, \dots, \alpha_k})_{A_{i_1 \dots i_\ell}}\right) \\
		&= \rmd \left(
			\sum_{\beta \in I}
				\rho_\beta ((\rmd \circ r)^{\ell - 1} \circ i)(\cdual{\alpha_0, \dots, \alpha_k})_{\beta A_{i_1 \dots i_\ell}} \right) \\
		&= \rmd \left(
			\sum_{j = 1}^\ell
				(-1)^{i_j - j + 1} \rho_{\alpha_j} ((\rmd \circ r)^{\ell - 1} \circ i)(\cdual{\alpha_0, \dots, \alpha_k})_{A_{i_1 \dots \hat{i}_j \dots i_\ell}} \right) \\
		&= \rmd \left(
			\sum_{j = 1}^\ell
				 \rho_{\alpha_{i_j}} (\ell - 1)!
					(-1)^{i_1 + \dots + i_\ell - j + 1}
					(\rmd \rho_{\alpha_{i_1}} \wedge \dots \wedge \rmd \hat{\rho}_{\alpha_{i_j}} \wedge \dots \wedge \rmd \rho_{\alpha_{i_\ell}}) \right) \\
		&=  \sum_{j = 1}^\ell
				(\ell - 1)!(-1)^{i_1 + \dots +  i_\ell}
					(\rmd \rho_{\alpha_{i_1}} \wedge \dots \wedge \rmd \rho_{\alpha_{i_\ell}}) \\
		&=  \ell!(-1)^{i_1 + \dots + i_\ell}
					(\rmd \rho_{\alpha_{i_1}} \wedge \dots \wedge \rmd \rho_{\alpha_{i_\ell}}) \qedhere \\
\end{align*}
\end{proof}
This lemma is most useful for the case of $\ell = k$, resulting in
\begin{align*}
	(-1)^{(k(k + 1)/2) - k}(\rmd \circ r)^k(j(c))_{\alpha_j}
		&= (-1)^{(k(k + 1)/2) - k}(\rmd \circ r)^k(j(c))_{\Alpha_{0 \dots \hat{j} \dots k}} \\
		&= k! (-1)^{j + k} (\rmd \rho_{\alpha_0} \wedge \dots \wedge \hat{\rmd\rho}_{\alpha_j} \wedge \dots \wedge \rmd \rho_{\alpha_k})
\end{align*}
\begin{remark}
While this lemma describes the isomorphism only for very particular cocycles, using linearity
one easily generalizes this to all cocycles. One just has to remember that this component
shows only a local description of this isomorphism i.e. the component $\alpha_j$ represents
the resulting differential form only on $\U_{\alpha_j}$, with unambigousity for overlapping
sets guarenteed by the construction of the isomorphism (and only for cocyles, not for general
cochains).
\end{remark}
Neither the exact values, nor the signs here are terribly important, important is that the
resulting differential form, restricted to $\U_{\alpha_j}$, is the wedge product of derivatives
of the partition of unities subordinate to $\U_{\alpha_0}, \dots, \hat{\U}_{\alpha_j}, \dots,
\U_{\alpha_k}$ and thus only takes on non-zero values on the intersection $\U_{\alpha_0}
\cap \dots \cap \U_{\alpha_k}$. Intuitively $]\alpha_0 \dots \alpha_k[$ gets mapped by the
isomorphism to a bump $k$-form on $\U_{\alpha_0 \dots \alpha_k}$.

Having this explicit description of the isomorphism enables us to prove that it agrees with the
map induced by refinements i.e. given two great covers $\mathfrak{U} \prec \mathfrak{V}$ of a
smooth manifold $M$ together with an appropiate map $\lambda: J \to I$ from the index set of
$\mathfrak{V}$ to the index set of $\mathfrak{U}$, we want the following diagram to commute
(with $\varphi_\mathfrak{U}, \varphi_\mathfrak{V}$ being the respective isomorphisms):
% https://q.uiver.app/#q=WzAsMyxbMCwwLCJcXGhhdHtIfV4qKFxcbWF0aGZyYWt7VX0pIl0sWzEsMCwiSF4qX1xcZHIoTSkiXSxbMSwxLCJcXGhhdHtIfV4qKFxcbWF0aGZyYWt7Vn0pIl0sWzAsMSwiXFx2YXJwaGlfe1xcbWF0aGZyYWt7VX19Il0sWzIsMSwiXFx2YXJwaGlfe1xcbWF0aGZyYWt7Vn19IiwyXSxbMCwyLCJcXGxhbWJkYV4qIiwyXV0=
\[\begin{tikzcd}
	{\hat{H}^*(\mathfrak{U})} & {H^*_\dr(M)} \\
	& {\hat{H}^*(\mathfrak{V})}
	\arrow["{\varphi_{\mathfrak{U}}}", from=1-1, to=1-2]
	\arrow["{\lambda^*}"', from=1-1, to=2-2]
	\arrow["{\varphi_{\mathfrak{V}}}"', from=2-2, to=1-2]
\end{tikzcd}\]
\begin{lemma}
The above diagram commutes.
\end{lemma}
\begin{proof}
We are only going to show that this statement holds for cocycles $[c] \in H^k(\mathfrak{U})$
of the form $c = \cdual{\alpha_0, \dots, \alpha_k}$, but the general case directly follows
from this.

Let $\{\zeta_\beta\}_{\beta \in J}$ be a partition of unity of $M$ subordinate to
$\mathfrak{V}$. This induces a partition of unity $\{\rho_\alpha\}_{\alpha \in I}$ of $M$
subordinate to $\mathfrak{U}$ that is defined for every $\alpha \in I$ as
\[
	\rho_\alpha \coloneqq \sum_{\beta \in \lambda^{-1}(\alpha)} \zeta_\beta
\]
Recall how $\lambda^*$ acts:
\begin{align*}
	\lambda^*(\cdual{\alpha_0, \dots, \alpha_k})
		= \sum_{
			\beta_0 \in \lambda^{-1}(\alpha_0),
			\dots
			\beta_k \in \lambda^{-1}(\alpha_k)
		} \cdual{\beta_0, \dots, \beta_k}
\end{align*}
Let $\beta \in J$ be arbitrary. If $\lambda(\beta) \notin \{\alpha_0, \dots, \alpha_k\}$
then $\beta$ is not going to appear on the right side and we can thus conclude that it
gets mapped by $\varphi_\mathfrak{V}$ to a differential form whose restriction to $\V_\beta$
is zero. At the same time $\V_\beta \subseteq \U_{\lambda(\beta)}$ by definition and since
$\lambda(\beta) \notin \{\alpha_0, \dots, \alpha_k\}$ we also know that the restriction of
$\varphi_\mathfrak{U}([c])$ to $\U_{\lambda(\beta)}$ (and thus also to $\V_\beta$) is zero.
Therefore the maps agree on $\V_\beta$ in this case.

If $\lambda(\beta) \in \{\alpha_0, \dots, \alpha_k\}$ we can assume w.l.o.g. that
$\lambda(\beta) = \alpha_0$. By the explicit description of the isomorphism, the restriction of
$\varphi_{\mathfrak{V}}(\lambda^*([c]))$ to $\V_\beta$ vanishes for all terms that do not include
$\beta$ and is thus equal to
\begin{align*}
	k! (-1)^k \sum_{\beta_1 \in \lambda^{-1}(\alpha_1), \dots, \beta_k \in \lambda^{-1}(\alpha_k)}
		\rmd \zeta_{\beta_1} \wedge \dots \wedge \rmd \zeta_{\beta_k}
\end{align*}
On the other hand, the restriction of $\varphi_{\mathfrak{U}}([c])$ to $\U_{\alpha_0}$ (and thus to $\V_\beta$) is by multilinearity of the wedge product
and linearity of the exterior derivative equal to
\begin{align*}
	k! (-1)^k (\rmd \rho_{\alpha_1} \wedge \dots \wedge \rho_{\alpha_k})
		= k! (-1)^k \sum_{\beta_1 \in \lambda^{-1}(\alpha_1), \dots, \beta_k \in \lambda^{-1}(\alpha_k)}
		\rmd \zeta_{\beta_1} \wedge \dots \wedge \rmd \zeta_{\beta_k}
\end{align*}
Thus the diagram commutes.
\end{proof}

\begin{corolarry}
Given a smooth manifold $M$ with a great cover $\mathfrak{U}$, there is a natural isomorphism
between $\hat{H}^*(M)$ and $\hat{H}^*(\mathfrak{U})$.
\end{corolarry}

